2026-07-10T05:20:43.8791290Z               "id": "6255b0d15d68151db7dd3b3cbdb4cb3674fa7fd1",
2026-07-10T05:20:43.8794963Z               "message": "Downgrade SOA serial-convention and banner/rDNS-mismatch from Warning to Info\n\nBoth fire on well-run domains and reflect normal operational reality rather than\ndeliverability problems:\n\n- SOA serial: the YYYYMMDDnn format is a convention (RFC 1912) with no operational\n  impact. Managed DNS providers (e.g. AWS Route 53) legitimately use a plain\n  counter starting at 1. The note moves from the SOA check's warnings to an\n  informational detail; the result was already Pass severity.\n- SMTP banner vs reverse DNS: a mismatch on an inbound MX is normal for\n  load-balanced/pooled fleets (Microsoft 365, Google), where the banner names the\n  edge node that answered rather than the connecting IP's PTR. The check now\n  reports Info instead of Warning, and the per-IP notes move from warnings to\n  details, with an explanatory line. A full match still reports Pass.\n\nCo-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.8 <noreply@anthropic.com>\nClaude-Session: https://claude.ai/code/session_01PD81wS9yngzumYcPpdYDsv",
2026-07-10T05:20:43.8799417Z               "timestamp": "2026-07-10T03:40:28Z",
