2026-07-10T05:20:43.8803874Z               "id": "0af0eee58f086ebf6af5993fc7cfc419afb29233",
2026-07-10T05:20:43.8812699Z               "message": "Fix IPv6 SMTP probes: use an address-family-correct socket, and calibrate severity\n\nRoot cause: SmtpProbeService created sockets with the parameterless `new TcpClient()`,\nwhich yields an IPv4-only (InterNetwork) socket. Connecting to a literal IPv6 address\nthrew `NotSupportedException: This protocol version is not supported.` immediately —\nbefore any network attempt — so every IPv6 port-25 probe failed regardless of the\nhost's real IPv6 capability. This made \"SMTP IPv6 Connectivity\" always warn for\ndual-stack providers (Microsoft 365, Google) even on IPv6-capable hosts.\n\n- Add CreateTcpClient(host): when the target is a literal IP, construct the TcpClient\n  with that IP's address family; hostnames keep the default path. Applied to all four\n  connect sites (SMTP probe, port probe, RCPT, relay). Construction on a host with no\n  IPv6 stack throws and is caught by the existing per-call try/catch (and the check is\n  already gated by NetworkCapabilities.HasIpv6).\n- SmtpIpv6ConnectivityCheck now only emits the domain-blaming \"stale AAAA\" Warning when\n  at least one IPv6:25 connection succeeded (proving this host can egress IPv6:25).\n  When none are reachable the result is ambiguous — could be the domain, or this host's\n  outbound IPv6:25 being blocked (ICMP ping does not prove port-25 egress) — so it\n  reports Info and explains how to disambiguate, instead of blaming the target.\n\nCo-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.8 <noreply@anthropic.com>\nClaude-Session: https://claude.ai/code/session_01PD81wS9yngzumYcPpdYDsv",
2026-07-10T05:20:43.8818283Z               "timestamp": "2026-07-10T03:54:14Z",
2026-07-10T05:20:43.8818638Z               "tree_id": "c23fac4a873d3ee76591b43ded92e1b7188bf093",
2026-07-10T05:20:43.8819159Z               "url": "https://github.com/pkinerd/ednsv/commit/0af0eee58f086ebf6af5993fc7cfc419afb29233"
2026-07-10T05:20:43.8819627Z             },
2026-07-10T05:20:43.8819820Z             {
2026-07-10T05:20:43.8820009Z               "author": {
2026-07-10T05:20:43.8820260Z                 "email": "noreply@anthropic.com",
2026-07-10T05:20:43.8820542Z                 "name": "Claude",
2026-07-10T05:20:43.8820783Z                 "username": "claude"
2026-07-10T05:20:43.8821015Z               },
2026-07-10T05:20:43.8821210Z               "committer": {
2026-07-10T05:20:43.8821471Z                 "email": "noreply@anthropic.com",
2026-07-10T05:20:43.8821742Z                 "name": "Claude",
2026-07-10T05:20:43.8821974Z                 "username": "claude"
2026-07-10T05:20:43.8822217Z               },
2026-07-10T05:20:43.8822415Z               "distinct": false,
2026-07-10T05:20:43.8822701Z               "id": "6a1b2b9a61f886215bc85f1edc96bd923b515789",
2026-07-10T05:20:43.8827945Z               "message": "Revert IPv6 socket-family change and self-calibration; keep the HasIpv6 gate\n\nThe original IPv6 SMTP failures were an IPv4-only network environment, not a code\nbug: the parameterless `new TcpClient()` already creates a dual-mode IPv6 socket on\nan IPv6-capable host (Socket.OSSupportsIPv6), so it handles IPv6 targets correctly.\nThe earlier \"IPv4-only socket\" reproduction was a no-IPv6-stack sandbox artifact.\n\n- Revert SmtpProbeService to its original `new TcpClient()` (removes CreateTcpClient);\n  now byte-identical to main.\n- Revert the self-calibration in SmtpIpv6ConnectivityCheck: any unreachable MX IPv6\n  address is again reported as a Warning (\"stale AAAA records cause delivery delays\").\n- Keep the NetworkCapabilities.HasIpv6 gate: the IPv6 checks (NS lame delegation, SOA\n  serial consistency, SMTP IPv6 connectivity) are skipped on hosts with no outbound\n  IPv6, which is the correct fix for the false positives — when the host does have\n  IPv6, the checks run and warn on genuine failures.\n\nCo-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.8 <noreply@anthropic.com>\nClaude-Session: https://claude.ai/code/session_01PD81wS9yngzumYcPpdYDsv",
